-- Italian Stocks Rebound; Banco Popolare, ERG, Fiat, Pininfarina Are Active
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s   a n d   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-11-15T17:06:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-15/italian-stocks-decline-banco-popolare-erg-intesa-shares-move-in-milan.html
Italy’s benchmark FTSE MIB Index
rose 163.44, or 0.8 percent, to 20,993.27 at the 5:30 p.m. close
in Milan, gaining for the first day in four.  The following companies either rose or fell in Italian
trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) retreated 3.5 percent to 3.54
euros. Italy’s fifth-biggest bank reported a 73 percent drop in
third quarter profit after lending income declined and a year-
earlier tax gain wasn’t repeated.       Bulgari SpA  (BUL IM), the world’s third-largest jeweler,
jumped 4.6 percent to 7.42 euros, after tumbling 5.8 percent
last week. In a note to investors today, CLSA wrote that
Hengdeli Holdings Ltd., the retail partner of Swatch Group AG in
China, is looking to step up an expansion into jewelry.  ERG SpA  (ERG IM) gained 2.3 percent to 9.92 euros after
Barclays Plc raised its recommendation for the refiner’s shares
to “overweight” from “equal weight.”  Fiat SpA  (F IM) gained 3 percent to 13.37 euros. The
company may sell auto-parts division Magneti Marelli SpA and a
stake in luxury carmaker Ferrari SpA before consolidating
Chrysler Group LLC, Chief Executive Officer  Sergio Marchionne 
told analysts.  Pininfarina SpA  (PINF IM) dropped 3 percent to 3.12 euros
after the car designer said its nine-month net loss widened to
33.8 million euros ($46 million) from 18.1 million euros a year
earlier. The company also said it expects a 2010 loss wider than
last year’s.  Premafin Finanziaria SpA  (PF IM) decreased 1.5 percent to
90 euro cents. The company, which controls insurer Fondiaria-Sai
SpA, may offer warrants to attract investors for its planned
rights offer, Il Messaggero reported, without saying where it
got the information.  Saras SpA  (SRS IM) retreated 4 percent to 1.44 euros after
Barclays downgraded the Milan-based operator of the Sarroch oil
refinery in the Mediterranean to “equal weight” from
“overweight.”  To contact the reporters on this story:
